&#xa0;
[normal]WWC0025[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Written evidence from UCAS Submission [bold]U[bold]nder-achievement in education by white working class children[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Executive Summary[bold]UCAS believes that tackling the issue of educational disadvantage must extend beyond the schooling years and that a holistic view needs to be taken by all those involved in education and progression.  This submission looks at the Higher Education (HE) application rates for working class pupils, application rates to HE by ethnic group and the split by sex. It suggests that it is not just the disadvantaged white males who are under-represented and that attention should focus on a wider group of disadvantaged male applicants.  It highlights the importance of transparent information and guidance alongside sustained outreach from an early age, as well as the need to address the importance of different qualification routes.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Introduction[bold]&#xa0;[bold]1.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]UCAS is the UK provider of shared admissions services for Higher Education (HE).  UCAS’ mission is to help 
[normal]all 
[normal]applicants to make the right choices for the right reasons with the right outcomes whether this is in their transition to work based, vocational training and apprenticeships or in taking other academic routes as well as facilitating (where appropriate) access to Higher Education.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]UCAS is seen by schools, colleges, universities and 
[normal]students
[normal] as a credible source for information on both the process of making applications and the range of education and training opportunities available.  UCAS therefore has a pivotal role to play in ensuring that all young people are engaged in exploring and making informed learning and career choices, and that they are supported in realising their aspirations and potentia
[normal]l
[normal].  UCAS also has a central role in supporting the higher education and schools and college sector through the provision of data that will help to identify potential barriers to young people achieving their aspirations through progression into HE. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]UCAS Progress
[normal] is a division of UCAS and is a UK provider of Course Search and Application services and online information and career planning tools for 12-19 year olds, currently focused
[normal] on supporting applications to p
[normal]ost-16 education and training.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]UCAS provides impartial information and advice, career and course information services which are available to 640,000 Year 10 and Year 11 learners, and application services to post-16 opportunities at over 4,000 schools, 6
[normal]th
[normal] Form and FE colleges and work-
[normal]based learning providers.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Why UCAS wishes to submit evidence to this Committee?[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]5.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]UCAS recognises that there are
[normal] a multitude of factors which contribute to under-achievement in education by white working class children, and that there has been extensive research conducted in this area. We believe that the issue of tackling educational disadvantage extends beyond the schooling years
[normal],
[normal] and UK universities also recognise the moral, social and economic imperative to address educational disadvantage. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Evidence[bold]7.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Whilst UCAS is not 
[normal]in a position to define what constitutes ‘underachievement’ for the purposes of this submission, UCAS can provide evidence on those students who apply to HE but are unsuccessful in gaining a place at any HE institution (including through Clearing).   We recognise that underachievement for the purposes of this Select Committee extends beyond this remit, including individuals who
[normal] don’t 
[normal]reach the stage of aspiring to apply to HE, but UCAS considers it useful to look at any patterns which may affect underachievement in accessing HE.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]8.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]UCAS 
[normal]holds data on 
[normal]appl
[normal]icants who apply to HE from dis
[normal]advantaged backgrounds. In addressing some of the factors considered to be responsible for under-achievement, evidence provided will take into account factors such as parental occupation and POLAR2 data 
[normal]of those applying to HE, 
[normal]differences between males and females applying to HE and the mixed profiles of qualifications types. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]UCAS can offer the following information for consideration by the Committee
[normal]:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]HE Application Rates for Working Class Pupils [bold]&#xa0;[bold]9.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Here we assume POLAR2 as a proxy for defining areas
[normal] 
[normal]which are more likely to contain working class families and pupils and take analysis from the UCAS 2013 Demand Report
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]The focus is on application rates which are a measure of the proportion of the population submitting an application for 
[normal]HE
[normal] through UCAS.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]10.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Further details on POLAR and its relativity to other measures of advantage in England can be found on the HEFCE website
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]11.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]UCAS data (
[normal]Figure 7 UCAS 2013 Demand Report
[normal]) 
[normal]shows the application rates for English 18 year olds by POLAR2, where quintile 5 (Q5) represents the most advantaged areas and quintile 1 (Q1) the most disadvantaged areas. Application rates for 18 year olds in England from all backgrounds have increased since 2004, with the largest increases for young people from the most disadvantaged backgrounds. The application rate of young people living in the most disadvantaged areas has increased by over 70 per cent (proportionally) between 2004 and 2013. This compares to an increase of 10 per cent proportionally in the most advantaged areas. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]12.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]In 2013, 18 year olds living in the most advantaged areas are 2.7 times more likely to apply for 
[normal]HE
[normal] than those living in the most disadvantaged areas. This is substantially less of a differential than in 2004, when 18 year olds living in the most advantaged areas were 4.3 times more likely to apply for 
[normal]HE
[normal] than those living in the most disadvantaged areas. This reduction is a result of the relatively larger growth in demand from disadvantaged areas over this period. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]13.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Figure 9
[normal] 
[normal]in the 
[normal]Demand Report 2013
[normal] 
[normal]shows
[normal] 
[normal]the application rates for 18 year olds in England by F
[normal]ree 
[normal]S
[normal]chool 
[normal]M
[normal]eal (FSM)
[normal] status at age 15, 2006 to 2013.
[normal] 
[normal]Pupils in independent schools are treated as not in receipt of 
[normal]FSMs
[normal] for this measure. On these definitions around 13% of the 18 year old population were in receipt of 
[normal]FSMs 
[normal]when aged 15. The application rate for 18 year olds in 2013 who were previously in receipt of 
[normal]FSMs
[normal] is 15% compared with 33% for those not in receipt of 
[normal]FSMs
[normal]. Pupils who had not been
[normal] in 
[normal]receipt of 
[normal]FSMs
[normal] were more than twice as likely to apply to HE in 2013 than those who had been in receipt of 
[normal]FSMs
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]14.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]In 2012, when the higher and more variable fees were introduced, the application rate of those not in receipt of 
[normal]FSMs
[normal] fell by 1.5 percentage
[normal] points (4.7% 
[normal]proportionally). In comparison, the application rate of those in receipt of 
[normal]FSMs
[normal] fel
[normal]l by 0.1 percentage points (0.8% 
[normal]proportionally). In 2013, the application rates increas
[normal]e for both groups by around 3.5% 
[normal]proportionally (and the application rate for those in receipt of 
[normal]FSMs
[normal] reached a new recorded high). 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Ethnicity[bold]&#xa0;[bold]15.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The analysis in 
[normal]the 
[normal]UCAS 2013 Demand Report 
[normal] 
[normal]is extended within the report to consider application rates by POLAR2 to Higher Tariff Institutions (Fig.23) and also by the ethnicity of those in state education.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]16.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Administrative records (source National Pupil Database, Department for Education) record an ethnic group for pupils in English state schools. This allows, through the same record linking method as used for the free school meal application rates, the application rate of pupils in each ethnic group to be estimated (this will be slightly lower than the actual value because only unambiguous links between the data sources are used). 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]17.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]There is a large range in the population size of the different groups. For instance, there are around 500,000 pupils recorded in the White ethnic group compared to around 2,000 pupils recorded in the Chinese ethnic group. This analysis uses the major group level classification of ethnic groups; it is possible that more detailed ethnic groups would show different application rate levels and trends. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]18.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Figure 10 shows the application rates by ethnic group estimated using this method. The application rate of pupils from all ethnic groups increases over the period. All ethnic groups also show the national pattern of a decrease against trend in application rates in 2012 followed by a return to increases in 2013 at approximately the trend rate. There are differences in both the level and trend rate of growth between groups. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]19.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Across the period, the Chinese ethnic group have consistently higher application rates, more than 50 per cent on this measure, compared with the other groups. The Asian ethnic group
[normal] have a
[normal]n application rate of around 40% 
[normal]on this measure in 2013. The Black, Mixed, White and Other ethnic groups have application rates in a relatively 
[normal]narrow range in 2013 between 29% 
[normal](White) and 3
[normal]4% 
[normal](Black). The largest increase in application rates across the period, and the largest increase in 2013, is observed for the Black ethnic group, for these pupils the applica
[normal]tion rate has increased from 20% in 2006 to 34% 
[normal]in 2013 (
[normal]a 70% 
[normal]proportional increase). 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Are application rates significantly worse for white working class boys than girls?[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]20.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Around 44% 
[normal]of the young English cohort applies to 
[normal]HE b
[normal]y age 19. 
[normal]The analysis in 
[normal]the 
[normal]UCAS 2013 Demand Report 
[normal](
[normal]Figure 8
[normal])
[normal] shows how this national rate is a mixture of different rates for men and women. For the cohort aged 18 in 2012, more (49
[normal]%
[normal]) women than men (38
[normal]%
[normal]) applied to 
[normal]HE
[normal] by age 19. For
[normal] this cohort young women are 29% 
[normal]more likely to apply than young men. This difference is slightly larger than in recent cycles, but within the range seen over the period.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]21.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]If we compare POLAR2 quintiles against the mean proportion of men and women between 2006 and 2013 (
[normal]T
[normal]able 1), we see that the percentage of men applying to HE decreases as the extent of disadvantage increases, but the reverse is the case for females.
[normal]&#xa0;
