[normal]Total[bold]42%[bold]58%[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Does the qualification type impact on application and entry rates to Higher Education?[bold]              [bold]23.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Additional data that the Committee may want to consider is the qualification type held by applicants and the effect that this has on entry rates. For example, 
[normal]y
[normal]oung people in more advantaged areas are substantially more likely to enter HE and hold
[normal] 
[normal]A
[normal]-
[normal]levels than those living in more disadvantaged areas.
[normal] 
[normal]More data on this can be found in the UCAS 2012 End of Cycle Report. 
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]24.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]One area that we would highlight as becoming more important in understanding the trends for HE admissions between different groups is the nature of qualification chosen post 16. In particular, the balance between a set of A levels and Vocational Qualifications, especially BTECs. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]25.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]DFE analysis shows that the proportions of young people attaining level 3 through a BTEC qualification has increased very rapidly (from 3% of 19 year olds in 2004 to 16% in 2012 
[normal]2012
[normal]), and the proportion qualified to level 3 with (solely) A levels is in sharp decline. The increase in the proportion of level 3 holders who have vocational qualifications has been disproportionately large for those in more disadvantaged groups where it is now the case that more gain level 3 through BTECs than A levels.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]26.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Separate 
[normal]DfE
[normal] data on exam entries shows that the proportion of students entered for purely academic qualifications has been in steady decline in recent years – from 70% in 2008 to 51% in 2012.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]27.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]We see this reflected in our application data with around half of higher performing accepted applicants from disadvantaged backgrounds holding BTECs, compared to fewer than one in ten from more advantaged groups. This may restrict choice for certain types of applicants as higher performing students holding BTECs are almost entirely absent from certain types of institutions.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Conclusions [bold]&#xa0;[bold]28.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The data shows us that whilst applications to 
[normal]HE
[normal] from the more disadvantaged groups 
[normal]are 
[normal]increas
[normal]ing
[normal], there is still a gulf between those app
[normal]lying from quintile 1 (most dis
[normal]advantaged areas) and quintile 5 (most advantaged). 
[normal]Pupils who had not been receipt of 
[normal]FSMs 
[normal]were more than twice as likely to apply to 
[normal]HE
[normal] in 2013 than those who had been in receipt of 
[normal]FSMs
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]29.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Data on the application rates by ethnic groups show
[normal]s
[normal] that whilst the Chinese and Asian ethnic groups have relatively high application rates, 
[normal]the Black, Mixed, White and Other ethnic groups have application rates in a relatively narrow range in 2013 with White applicants having the lowest application rate across the period. The largest increase in 2013, is observed for the Black ethnic group, where the application rate has increased has increased 
[normal]from 20% in 2006 to 34% in 2013 (a 70% 
[normal]proportional increase). 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]30.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]It is also evident that there are large disparities between applications to 
[normal]HE
[normal] from men and women, again further compounding the gap between the educational achievements of boys and girls during their secondary education.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]31.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]It can be concluded that in terms of aspiring to 
[normal]HE
[normal], the gap between young men and women applying is significantly worse for men. Young women were a third more likely to enter 
[normal]HE 
[normal]in 2012 than men, and the majority of the fall in entry rate in 2012 was amongst men. Amongst 18 year olds, women were a third more likely to enter 
[normal]HE
[normal] in 2012 than men
[normal]. W
[normal]omen remain more likely to 
[normal]enter 
[normal]HE
[normal] than men are to 
[normal]even 
[normal]apply
[normal] 
[normal]to HE
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]32.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The proportion of men applying to 
[normal]HE
[normal] also reduces as POLAR2 quintile increases (i.e. the extent of disadvantage increases).  So the more disadvantaged young men are, the less likely they are to aspire to pursue 
[normal]HE
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Recommendations[bold]34.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]To be able to address the issue of under-achievement in education by white working class children, an holistic approach needs to be taken by all those involved in education and progression, starting from early years through to secondary and higher education and into employability and lifelong learning.  This requires consistent and regular intervention, targeted particular at those groups who are most at risk of dropping out of education or becoming a NEET.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]35.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Our evidence also suggests that it is not just the disadvantaged white males who are under-represented, certainly in applying to HE.  Our data would suggest that the Committee needs to focus on the needs of a much wider group of disadvantaged male applicants including the black and mixed ethnic groups. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]38.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]This evidence is concurrent with other research which shows that long term, sustained  outreach is key to raising aspirations from an
[normal] 
[normal]early age. OFFA is urging universities to consider drawing up plans for working with primary school children to raise their ambitions towards HE. 
[normal]E
[normal]xploring and explaining possible outcomes and career paths can have a motivational effect on how students view the purpose of education and training,
[normal] 
[normal]how they engage with their studies and develop positive aspirations. 
[normal]Universities need to continue to reach out to all potential applicants
[normal], for example through
[normal] 
[normal]through
[normal] consistent and targeted outreach in the form of summer schools and visit days.  
[normal]C
[normal]ase studies
[normal] also show that enabling
[normal] undergraduates
[normal] or
[normal] student mentors 
[normal]to spend time in 
[normal]schools is an excellent way of 
[normal]ins
[normal]piring young people
[normal] by showing what can be achieved and the barriers that others have overcome.
[normal] 
[normal]. 
[normal]S
[normal]tudents who have participated in university summer schools are already expressly
[normal] 
[normal]encouraged to include this information in their UCAS applications, and this information can be taken into consideration by admissions staff when applications are being assessed. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]39.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Additionally, we would recommend to the Committee that if under-represented children are to have a fair chance of entering the more selective universities, the issue of decreasing participation in A levels must be addressed.
